ce:section.ce:para:
The synthesis method of N-CQDs in this work is demonstrated in (Scheme. 1
                     ). In this study, WMS was used as a nitrogen and carbon source, and LJ contains a large amount of citric acid (CA), which is used as a carbon source. The WMS and LJ with the appropriate molar amount with concentrated sulphuric acid can produce N-CQDs within a short time period. CA is a widespread candidate for synthesizing CDs due to its capability to form carbonaceous material during the reaction (Zhao et al., 2022). Compared with other carbonyl groups in glutaraldehyde and hydroxyl groups in glycerol, the carboxyl groups of CA easily react with amine groups of WMS (Liu et al., 2016). The reaction between WMS and LJ containing CA assists in the formation of the C-N framework with high yield and outstanding stability (Li et al., 2014; Meng et al., 2022). The surface morphology of as-prepared N-CQDs was analyzed by TEM analysis. As represented in Fig. S1, the synthesized N-CQDs were highly crystalline in nature. They are spherical, monodispersed, and uniformly dispersed with very little aggregation (Meng et al., 2022). Fig. S1
                     b shows the narrow size distribution of these N-CQDs, which ranged from 3.4 to 7.5 nm. Most of the particles had an average diameter of about 5.33 nm, according to a Gaussian fit of the histogram produced via the particle's size distribution (De et al., 2023).
